      "summary": "Betobeto-san is a harmless but eerie yōkai from Japanese folklore known primarily through sound rather than sight.",
      "full": "Betobeto-san is a harmless but eerie yōkai from Japanese folklore known primarily through sound rather than sight. The name is onomatopoetic, representing the sound of wooden geta (traditional Japanese sandals) clacking on pavement—\\\"beto-beto\\\" or \\\"beta-beta.\\\" This yōkai manifests as invisible footsteps that follow solitary travelers on dark roads at night, matching their pace exactly. While the constant footsteps behind can be deeply unnerving, Betobeto-san causes no physical harm and will politely depart if acknowledged correctly. The yōkai embodies the anxiety of being followed in darkness and represents Japan's rich tradition of auditory supernatural phenomena."
